                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding contemporary="unknown">
                                <p>Medieval binding. Brown leather over wooden boards. 5 pairs of raised bands and 2 endbands. <locus from="RCO" to="RCO" scheme="other"/>, top of page, half of a medieval parchment lable with nails in it, text in black ink: <quote>legenda</quote>. <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/>, ink on paper label: <quote>N:o 21. Jac. Jannensis Legenda aurea Sanctorum</quote>; stamped in gold: <quote>A 158</quote>; ink on paper label:<quote> e. 30. 6. 13</quote>.</p>
                                <p>The endleaves consist of 2 bifolia from <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102566">Petrus Comestor</persName>’s Historia scholastica. These fragments seem to be written by the same or a similar hand as the main text</p>
                                <p>
                                    <dimensions type="binding">
                                        <height quantity="270" unit="mm"/>
                                        <width quantity="195" unit="mm"/>
                                        <depth quantity="85" unit="mm"/>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </p>
                                <condition>Leather heavily torn. Board visible on <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/>. Remains of clasps (nails on <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/>), corner and centre pieces. Wormholes all over covers. New leather added to </condition>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <origDate notAfter="1400" notBefore="1301">14th century</origDate>
                            </p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p/>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>The manuscript is listed in Vossius’s catalogue from 1651 (U 202:1) and has belonged to the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100004">National Library</orgName> since. It probably came to Sweden as spoils of war or was bought on the continent by <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/100086">Queen Christina</persName>. There are 3 signa on the <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/>. The older signum <quote>21</quote> is found in the catalogue from 1734 (U 125e); <quote>e. 30.6.13.</quote> is found in Hammarsköld’s catalogue from the 19th century (U 133); <quote>A 158</quote> (current signum).</p>
                        </provenance>
                    </history>
